            <div type="a">
                <column>01</column>
                <head>Wants of Staunton</head>
                <origin/>
                <commentary/>
                <transcript>
                    <p/>
                </transcript>
                <trailer/>
                <names/>
                <summary>The paper declares that Staunton is in need of a "first-class ten-pin
                    alley" and a bath-house.</summary>
                <note/>
                <look/>
            </div>
            <div type="a">
                <column>01</column>
                <head/>
                <origin/>
                <commentary/>
                <transcript>
                    <p/>
                </transcript>
                <trailer/>
                <names/>
                <summary>The paper declares that the sanitary conditions of Staunton's streets are
                    "horrible" and calls on police and Street Commissioners to enforce regulations.</summary>
                <note/>
                <look/>
            </div>
            <div type="a">
                <column>01</column>
                <head>Wesleyan Female Institute, Staunton</head>
                <origin/>
                <commentary/>
                <transcript>
                    <p/>
                </transcript>
                <trailer/>
                <names/>
                <summary>The paper prints testimony praising the Wesleyan Female Institute.</summary>
                <note/>
                <look/>
            </div>
            <div type="a">
                <column>02</column>
                <head/>
                <origin/>
                <commentary/>
                <transcript>
                    <p/>
                </transcript>
                <trailer/>
                <names/>
                <summary>The ladies of the Methodist Church will hold a three-day fair beginning
                    tomorrow at the town hall.</summary>
                <note/>
                <look/>
            </div>
            <div type="a">
                <column>02</column>
                <head>Commencement Week</head>
                <origin/>
                <commentary/>
                <transcript>
                    <p/>
                </transcript>
                <trailer/>
                <names/>
                <summary>The paper reports that commencement week has left Staunton's scholars in
                    commotion with exams, and closing exercises.</summary>
                <note/>
                <look/>
            </div>
            <div type="a">
                <column>02</column>
                <head>A Trio of Virginians</head>
                <origin>Hagerstown Mail</origin>
                <commentary/>
                <transcript>
                    <p/>
                </transcript>
                <trailer/>
                <names>
                    <name>
                        <ln>Garber</ln>
                        <fn>A. M.</fn>
                        <sf/>
                        <pf>Maj.</pf>
                    </name>
                </names>
                <summary>Maj. A. M. Garber, editor of the Valley Virginian, was one of three
                    Virginians to recently visit Hagerstown.</summary>
                <note/>
                <look/>
            </div>
            <div type="a">
                <column>03</column>
                <head>Public Gardens</head>
                <origin/>
                <commentary/>
                <transcript>
                    <p/>
                </transcript>
                <trailer/>
                <names/>
                <summary>The paper reports that Staunton's Public Gardens are not large enough to
                    meet demand, causing many families to send to Richmond for vegetables. The two
                    hotels and many "first class boarding houses" in town make more garden space
                    necessary.</summary>
                <note/>
                <look/>
            </div>
            <div type="s">
                <column>03</column>
                <head>Marriages</head>
                <origin/>
                <commentary/>
                <transcript>
                    <p/>
                </transcript>
                <trailer/>
                <names>
                    <name>
                        <ln>Bell</ln>
                        <fn>William A.</fn>
                        <sf/>
                        <pf/>
                    </name>
                    <name>
                        <ln>Nottingham</ln>
                        <fn>Elizabeth E.</fn>
                        <sf/>
                        <pf/>
                    </name>
                    <name>
                        <ln>Bunting</ln>
                        <fn>R. F.</fn>
                        <sf/>
                        <pf>Rev.</pf>
                    </name>
                </names>
                <summary>William A. Bell of Augusta County and Miss Elizabeth E. Nottingham of
                    Nashville were married in Nashville on June 16th by the Rev. R. F. Bunting. The
                    couple left on the evening train for their "future home in the beautiful Valley
                    of Virginia."</summary>
                <note/>
                <look/>
            </div>
